Opening Files

Since well be working in R Studio and not base R, lets make sure .r and .rmd files open in the right program. For Macs, two-finger-click on a file of each type, select Get Info, and check Open With. If its not R Studio, be sure to click Change All. For Windows, the path is Start > Settings > Apps > Default Apps, and then Choose default apps by file type. Check to make sure that it worked.

Great! Now that we are in R Studio, lets open a dataset. Go to the class Github page (https://github.com/shikhar46/quantmethods), and download the dataset analysis_lottery_household.csv. This is from one of the papers we talked about on Wednesday, and it has 13,414 observations of Southern households that had a child in Georgia between 1829 and 1833, when Cherokee lands were distributed to white citizens by lottery.

How do we open this dataset so that we can work with it? Base R has a read.csv function, but Professor Coppock strongly prefers that we use read_csv. To access that function, we need to go on two small detours to learn about packages and directories.

Packages

  • A big part of the reason that R and R Studio are so great is that they are open-source, meaning that anyone can contribute code to make them better. One of the ways this happens is when people develop new tools, and then save them as a package for anyone to download and use.

  • The thing to remember about packages is that the first time you want to use one, you have to download it from the internet using install.packages, and give the name in quotation marks. Every time after that, you load them up using library and no quotation marks. A little ideosyncratic, but just roll with it.

  • The first package were going to install is actually a package of packages: the Tidyverse. It contains two packages that we will use frequently, dplyr and ggplot2, as well as the package that contains read_csv. Give the following code a try:

install.packages("tidyverse")
library(tidyverse)

Directories

  • R Studio needs to know where a file is in order to open it. There are two ways to do this: tell R Studio exactly what folder that file is in, or set the working directory (current folder) to the same location as our file. Lets find out what folder R Studio is working in right now:
getwd() #"Get working directory"
## [1] "/Users/james/Dropbox/504/sections"
  • OK, thats not the same as where my file is, which is in /Users/james/Downloads. Below, Ill change the working directory to that folder. Note the quotation marks!
setwd("/Users/james/Downloads")

# Advanced tip: the tilde (~) is a shortcut for your home directory, which for me is /Users/james. So I could also have run: setwd("~/Downloads")

Now were ready to open our dataset. Im actually going to call it ourdata.

ourdata <- read_csv("analysis_lottery_household.csv")

If I didnt want to change my working directory, I could also run:

ourdata <- read_csv("/Users/james/Downloads/analysis_lottery_household.csv")

dplyr

Dplyr is a toolbox for manipulating data. Usually, the dataset we load into our computers are not ready for analysis, and we need to do a bit more work to get it the way we want. People use an interesting variety of verbs for this kind of work: tidying, cleaning, wrangling, etc.

Dplyr is a set of verbs (functions) that perform the basic tasks of data wrangling.

  • filter returns rows of the dataset that match whatever logical conditions you set.
  • select returns columns of the dataset that match whatever logical conditions you set.
  • rename does exactly what it sounds like: it renames a variable.
  • mutate creates a new variable

Lets try them out on our dataset:

filter(ourdata, state=="Florida" & hh_size > 10)

group_by( ) and summarise( )

There are two more dplyr verbs that are frequently used together. group_by splits the data into subgroups, and summarise allows you to calculate something about each group. For instance, lets check to see how family size varied by state:

by_state <- group_by(ourdata, state)
summarise(by_state, avg_num_kids = mean(children_size))
## # A tibble: 11 x 2
##    state          avg_num_kids
##    <chr>                 <dbl>
##  1 Alabama                4.79
##  2 Arkansas               5.03
##  3 Florida                4.56
##  4 Georgia                4.44
##  5 Louisiana              4.72
##  6 Mississippi            4.75
##  7 North Carolina         4.44
##  8 South Carolina         4.52
##  9 Tennessee              4.29
## 10 Texas                  4.35
## 11 Virginia               4

Thats sort of cool, but instead of listing the states alphabetically, lets list them by the average number of kids. For this, well need our final dplyr verbs: arrange and desc( ).

kids_by_state <- summarise(by_state, avg_num_kids = mean(children_size))
arrange(kids_by_state, desc(avg_num_kids))
## # A tibble: 11 x 2
##    state          avg_num_kids
##    <chr>                 <dbl>
##  1 Arkansas               5.03
##  2 Alabama                4.79
##  3 Mississippi            4.75
##  4 Louisiana              4.72
##  5 Florida                4.56
##  6 South Carolina         4.52
##  7 North Carolina         4.44
##  8 Georgia                4.44
##  9 Texas                  4.35
## 10 Tennessee              4.29
## 11 Virginia               4

The Pipe: %>%

Dplyr verbs work well together. Sometimes, you dont want to work through one step at a time; you want to do multiple steps at once. In the bad old days, people wrote code this way: f(g(x)), where you do function G of object x, before doing function F of the result. This could get very confusing as the nested parentheses grew deeper. Furthermore, we read from left to right, not inside out. The dplyr philosophy says that we should write: x %>% g() %>% f(). Translation: take X, G it, then F it. Much more readable! The %>% symbol is called the pipe, and it passes arguments from left to right. You can either type it manually, or use CMD + SHIFT + M on Macs, or CNTRL + SHIFT + M on PCs.

Example: Among those who did not own real estate, did families with slaves still send their men to fight at a higher rate?

# Note that by specifying our data at the outset, we can skip the first argument of these functions
ourdata2 %>% 
  filter(real_property==0) %>%
  group_by(slaves_binary) %>% 
  summarise(avg_participation_rate = mean(frac_confdr))
## # A tibble: 2 x 2
##   slaves_binary avg_participation_rate
##   <lgl>                          <dbl>
## 1 FALSE                          0.677
## 2 TRUE                           0.735

Stylistic note: after every pipe, start a new line!

ggplot

ggplot can help you make beautiful figures. Personally, I dont think the grammar makes as much sense as dplyr does, but you only have to remember a basic recipe: ggplot(name of dataset, aes(x = something, y = something else)) + type of plot you want

Types of plots in ggplot are called geoms. Lets look at some common ones. Im going to only use the data from Alabama, because it is easier to see 2000 points than 13,000 points.

al_data <- ourdata %>% filter(state=="Alabama")

# A histogram. You can change the number of "bins" if you so desire.
ggplot(al_data, aes(x = children_size)) + geom_histogram()
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

# A scatterplot.
ggplot(al_data, aes(x = children_size, y = sons_size)) + geom_point()

# Adding the "jitter" geom adds some random noise to the points, so that they are not all on top of one another.
ggplot(al_data, aes(x = children_size, y = sons_size)) + geom_point() + geom_jitter()

Note how you can use + signs to slowly build up a plot.

fig1 <- ggplot(ourdata2, aes(x = state))
fig1 <- fig1 + geom_bar()
fig1 <- fig1 + theme_bw()
fig1 + theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = -45)) #rotate labels

Coefficient Plots

Take a look at Table 7/Figure 6 of this paper: https://www.princeton.edu/~jkastell/Tables2Graphs/graphs.pdf

Coef plots are way easier to interpret than tables of regression output. Lets make one with our dataset. First well need to load a package and run a model.

library(estimatr)
## Warning: package 'estimatr' was built under R version 3.4.4
## Warning: the `broom` package version 0.5.0 or earlier is loaded.
## Please upgrade `broom` or `tidy` methods may not work as expected.
model1 <- lm_robust(formula = frac_confdr_count_men ~ treat, data = ourdata)
out1 <- tidy(model1)

fig2 <- ggplot(out1, aes(x = term, y = estimate))
fig2 <- fig2 + geom_point() + geom_abline(slope = 0, intercept = 0, lty = 2)
fig2 <- fig2 + geom_errorbar(aes(ymin = estimate - 1.96*std.error, ymax = estimate + 1.96*std.error), width = .01)
fig2 + expand_limits(y = c(0, .7))

The figure above uses a few different geoms: ab_line to draw a dashed line at y = 0, point to make points, and errorbar to show a 95% confidence interval.

Install the package nycflights13 and then load it from the library. It wont show up in the upper-right box, but the data is there, in a tibble called flights. Take a look at the data with View(flights). Try to make a few plots.

Faceting

Just as we group_by when analyzing data statistically, so might we want to break the analysis into small subgroups when we examine the data visually. In the Tidyverse, this is called faceting. Beyond the Tidyverse, you might hear them called small multiples. To facet by a variable, add this to your code: + facet_wrap(~ variable). Lets see how the distribution of flight times varied by airport.

library(nycflights13)
## Warning: package 'nycflights13' was built under R version 3.4.4
ggplot(flights, aes(x = air_time)) + geom_histogram() + facet_wrap(~ origin)
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.
## Warning: Removed 9430 rows containing non-finite values (stat_bin).

knitr and LaTeX

So youve done all your analysis, your results are robust, and your evidence is beautiful. Time to share it with the world!

If youre writing lots of code, its best to compile your results in R Markdown. (This document was created in R Markdown.) When it comes time to write a paper, and you only need to include a few figures, it might be time to use LaTeX.

To write in R Markdown, we will first install a package called knitr. (You should already be a pro at installing packages!) However, we are not going to open it in from the library. Instead, go all the way to the top of the screen and click on File > New File > R Markdown.

A new R Markdown file should pop up, full of helpful hints. Click on the Knit button on the top of the screen to compile it into a pdf. Congratulations! Youre ready to begin doing problem sets!
